</div><div class="comments"><div class="comment-arrow"><img src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_commentarrow_top.gif"></div><div class="comment" id="comment_25097"><span class="header"><a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/users/156690" class="bold">MichaelK</a> <span class="wide">|</span> <b>January 12, 2011 at  4:38 PM</b><img class="star" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_star_dark.gif" alt="Comment Rating" title="Comment Rating" /><strong><span id="comment_rating_25097">2</span></strong></span><br /></span><div class="body"><p>ADC range is 0-1023. If 1023 (the maximum possible value) is supposed to mean Vpin = Vcc, then for Vcc=5V:</p>

<pre>Vpin = 1023*5000/1024 = 4995 mV
</pre>

<p>which is wrong. But:</p>

<pre>Vpin = 1023*5000/1023 = 5000 mV
</pre>

<p>which is the correct value.
For an ADC value of 0 we still get zero, which is correct:</p>

<pre>Vpin = 0*5000/1023 = 0 mV
</pre>

<p>So it seems to me that the formula should use 1023, rather than 1024, or in other words, it should use the maximum allowed value, rather than the number of possible values.</p>

<p>In practice though, the error is very small either way (about 0.1%), and in a hobby system you'll probably get a larger error just from the various system noises.</p>
</div></div><div class="comment" id="comment_24969"><span class="header"><a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/users/158040" class="bold">FjarrKontroll</a> <span class="wide">|</span> <b>January 12, 2011 at  9:02 AM</b><img class="star" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_star_dark.gif" alt="Comment Rating" title="Comment Rating" /><strong><span id="comment_rating_24969">1</span></strong></span><br /></span><div class="body"><p>Yes, there are 1024 numbers, however the calculation needs a base of zero. If your minimum ADC value is 1, you can never calculate a voltage of zero.</p>

<p>((ADC Value)*(System Voltage))/(Max ADC Value) = Voltage on Pin</p>

<p>Here is the minimum calculable voltage using the current equation:
(1*3300)/1024 = 3.22265625</p>

<p>And here it is with a minimum of zero:
(0*3300)/1023 = 0</p>

<p>I could be wrong of course so do correct me if I am, but it just seems flawed to me because only 1023 values are ideally non-zero. That said, should I still use 1024 for Free Day? :P</p>
</div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="comment" id="comment_23068"><span class="header"><a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/users/92430" class="bold">dksmall</a> <span class="wide">|</span> <b>December 16, 2010 at  7:00 PM</b><img class="star" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_star_dark.gif" alt="Comment Rating" title="Comment Rating" /><strong><span id="comment_rating_23068">1</span></strong></span><br /></span><div class="body"><p>Datasheets for the AVR's use 1024.  And now equations 1 &amp; 2 don't show up.</p>
</div></div><div class="comment" id="comment_24938"><span class="header"><a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/users/91266" class="bold">Tom</a> <span class="wide">|</span> <b>January 11, 2011 at  7:01 PM</b><img class="star" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_star_dark.gif" alt="Comment Rating" title="Comment Rating" /><strong><span id="comment_rating_24938">1</span></strong></span><br /></span><div class="body"><p>Thanks, I was wondering how to tie the value from ADC back to an expected voltage.  This correlates well with my measurements with a Sharp IR sensor and its datasheet.<br />
Suggestion:  How about expanding this to a "Word-sized" tutorial and explain how adding a voltage reference (positive and/or negative ) changes the equation?</p>
</div></div><div class="comment" id="comment_25126"><span class="header"><a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/users/184541" class="bold">Adamws</a> <span class="wide">|</span> <b>January 12, 2011 at  7:32 PM</b><img class="star" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_star_dark.gif" alt="Comment Rating" title="Comment Rating" /><strong><span id="comment_rating_25126">1</span></strong></span><br /></span><div class="body"><p>The original equation wasn't necessarily incorrect, but the interpretation of the values need to follow the equation that is used.  The 10-bit ADC contains 1024 different values each representing a range of voltages not one singular analog voltage.  This is due to the fact that most common ADCs operate using comparators.  With this in mind, the equation is V<em>analog = (V</em>ref / 2^n)<em>V<em>digital; where V</em>analog is not a singular voltage!  For example, if the reading 1023 is received by your favorite microcontroller (on a 3.3V system) it should not be interpreted as (3.3/1024)</em>1023 = 3.2967V but as an analog voltage in the range represented by the digital value 1023 and 1024 or 3.2967V and 3.3V.  Furthermore, the same reading of digital zero should not be interpreted as 0 analog volts; rather an analog voltage existing between 0 volts and 3.222mV.  If you choose to use the equation V<em>analog = (V</em>ref / (2^n-1))*V_digital the result should be interpreted as an analog voltage in the range between V_digital and V_digital-1.  However, the interpretation of V_digital=0 falls apart as the value should NOT be interpreted as ranging between 0V and -3.22mV!  This is why the first equation given herein is a more correct equation.  I believe it should be changed back above.  All of this may be rather silly though given that many of these ADCs we are discussing here have a error equal to ~1 LSB or 3.22mV in the above example.</p>
</div><div class="comments"><div class="comment-arrow"><img src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_commentarrow_top.gif"></div><div class="comment" id="comment_25146"><span class="header"><a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/users/37794" class="bold">AdamTolley</a> <span class="wide">|</span> <b>January 12, 2011 at  8:34 PM</b><img class="star" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_star_dark.gif" alt="Comment Rating" title="Comment Rating" /><strong><span id="comment_rating_25146">1</span></strong></span><br /></span><div class="body"><p>Soooo many problems arise when we forget that a number at a given precision does not represent an infinitesimally small point on the number line.  </p>

<p>Thanks for that clarification.  </p>
</div></div></div></div><div class="comment" id="comment_25172"><span class="header"><a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/users/28595" class="bold">Member28595</a> <span class="wide">|</span> <b>January 12, 2011 at 11:13 PM</b><img class="star" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_star_dark.gif" alt="Comment Rating" title="Comment Rating" /><strong><span id="comment_rating_25172">1</span></strong></span><br /></span><div class="body"><p>For a 10-bit ADC with a referernce voltage of 5 volts, you cannot convert 5 volts.  The maximum voltage you can represent is 1023/1024*5 or 4.995 (and change) volts.  </p>
</div></div><div class="comment" id="comment_25173"><span class="header"><a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/users/57151" class="bold">eewestcoaster</a> <span class="wide">|</span> <b>January 12, 2011 at 11:24 PM</b><img class="star" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_star_dark.gif" alt="Comment Rating" title="Comment Rating" /><strong><span id="comment_rating_25173">1</span></strong></span><br /></span><div class="body"><p>I can't remember formulas to save my life.  I always break up the last formula you show there into two slightly smaller parts so it sticks.  </p>

<p>First, I find out what the value is in percent.  That is, this is 377 out of a possible 1024 values, which is 0.368 (36.8%).  Multiplying that by the maximum voltage level gives you the actual measured voltage at the pin, in this case 5V * 0.368 = 1.84V.  </p>

<p>It's the same equation, but I find that this makes it easier for me to remember.  Mainly because it applies to a wider range of situations - for example, my hobby projects may use 5V but at work I find industrial systems that all seem to prefer 10V or 24V. The math is exactly the same - find the percentage, multiply by the max voltage.  </p>

<p>Protip: works great for tracking the position of a rotary encoder, too!  If you've counted 164 counts from your 200 count/rev encoder, you know you've gone 164/200 = 0.82 revolutions.  You want that in degrees?  Multiply by 360 degrees/rev --> 0.82 * 360 = 295.2 deg.  Radians? Multiply by 2<em>pi --> 0.82 * (2</em>pi) = 5.15 rad.  Arc-minutes?  Arc-seconds?  You get the idea.</p>

<p>The fewer formulas I have to remember, the better!</p>
</div></div><div class="comment" id="comment_25177"><span class="header"><a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/users/170696" class="bold">yardleydobon</a> <span class="wide">|</span> <b>January 13, 2011 at 12:16 AM</b><img class="star" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_star_dark.gif" alt="Comment Rating" title="Comment Rating" /><strong><span id="comment_rating_25177">1</span></strong></span><br /></span><div class="body"><p>The datasheet for the ATmega168 gives the equation:
ADC = (Vin*1024)/Vref</p>

<p>"0x000 represents analog ground, and 0x3FF represents the selected reference voltage minus one LSB."</p>

<p>However, because of quantization error you can't just simply use an algebraic manipulation to get Vin given ADC. You can however get an approximation of Vin given ADC. There are two ways to think about it.</p>

<p>1) Fraction of full scale (1023 --> Vref):<br />
f = (ADC/1023)<br />
Vin ~ Vref*f</p>

<p>or<br />
2) Multiple of resolution (1023 --> Vref-Q):<br />
Q = Vref/1024<br />
Vin ~ ADC*Q</p>

<p>Which formula you use depends on how you compare your measurements to the reference data. I believe most people find the fraction of full scale method more intuitive.</p>
</div></div><div class="comment" id="comment_26614"><span class="header"><a href="http://www.sparkfun.com/users/55277" class="bold">Ryan</a> <span class="wide">|</span> <b>January 14, 2011 at  5:42 AM</b><img class="star" src="http://dlnmh9ip6v2uc.cloudfront.net/images/framework/icon_star_dark.gif" alt="Comment Rating" title="Comment Rating" /><strong><span id="comment_rating_26614">1</span></strong></span><br /></span><div class="body"><p>The last set of equations works well for DACs and stays crunchy in milk! But why shift the decimals needlessly? Most electronic equations stay in the full unit when calculating Amps, Volts, Watts  etc... its much less confusing to look at 5 as five volts then 5000 as 5000 mV (or 5 volts!) </p>
</div></div></div>
